\par }\pard\plain \fi567\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\lang1033\cgrid0 
I hardly thought it likely that Mrs. Price Ridley had anything so dramatic in view, but I did wonder what had taken her to the police station. Had she really got evidence of importance, or that she thought of importance, to offer? At any rate, we should
 soon know.
\par We found Mrs. Price Ridley talking at a high rate of speed to a somewhat bewildered\_looking police constable. That she was extremely indignant I knew from the way the bow in her hat was trembling. Mrs. Price Ridley wears what, I believe, are kn
own as "Hats for Matrons" \emdash 
 they make a speciality of them in our adjacent town of Much Benham. They perch easily on a superstructure of hair and are somewhat overweighted with large bows of ribbon. Griselda is always threatening to get a matron's hat.
\par Mrs. Price Ridley paused in her flow of words upon our entrance.
\par "Mrs. Price Ridley?" inquired Colonel Melchett, lifting his hat.
\par "Let me introduce Colonel Melchett to you, Mrs. Price Ridley," I said. "Colonel Melchett is our Chief Constable."
\par Mrs. Price Ridley looked at me coldly, but produced the semblance of a gracious smile for the colonel.
\par "We've just been round to your house, Mrs. Price Ridley," explained the colonel, "and heard you had come down here."
\par Mrs. Price Ridley thawed altogether.
\par "Ah!" she said, "I'm glad }{\i\lang1033\cgrid0 some}{\lang1033\cgrid0  notice is being taken of the occurrence. Disgraceful, I call it. Simply disgraceful."
\par There is no doubt that murder is disgraceful, but it is not the word I should use to describe it myself. It surprised Melchett too, I could see.
\par "Have you any light to throw upon the matter?" he asked.
\par "That's your business. It's the business of the police. What do we pay rates and taxes for, I should like to know?"
\par One wonders how many times that query is uttered in a year!
\par "We're doing our best, Mrs. Price Ridley," said the Chief Constable.
\par "But the man here hadn't even heard of it till I told him about it!" cried the lady.
\par We all looked at the constable.
\par "Lady been rung up on the telephone," he said. "Annoyed. Matter of obscene language, I understand."
\par "Oh! I see." The colonel's brow cleared. "We've been talking at cross purposes. You came down here to make a complaint, did you?"
\par Melchett is a wise man. He knows that when it is a question of an irate middle\_aged lady, there is only one thing to be done \emdash  to listen to her. When she has said all that she wants to say, there is a chance that she will listen to you.
\par Mrs. Price Ridley surged into speech.
\par "Such disgraceful occurrences ought to be prevented. They ought not to occur. To be rung up in one's own house and insulted \emdash 
 yes, insulted. I'm not accustomed to such things happening. Ever since the war there has been a loosening of moral fibre. Nobody minds what they say, and as to the clothes they wear \emdash "
\par "Quite," said Colonel Melchett hastily. "What happened exactly?"
\par Mrs. Price Ridley took breath and started again.
\par "I was rung up \emdash "
\par "When?"
\par "Yesterday afternoon \emdash  evening to be exact. About half\_past six. I went to the telephone, suspecting nothing. Immediately I was foully attacked, threatened \emdash "
\par "What actually was said?"
\par Mrs. Price Ridley got slightly pink.
\par "That I decline to state."
\par "Obscene language," murmured the constable in a ruminative bass.
\par "Was bad language used?" asked Colonel Melchett
\par "It depends on what you call bad language."
\par "Could you understand it?" I asked.
\par "Of course I could understand it."
\par "Then it couldn't have been bad language," I said.
\par Mrs. Price Ridley looked at me suspiciously.
\par "A refined lady," I explained, "is naturally unacquainted with bad language."
\par "It wasn't that kind of thing," said Mrs. Price Ridley. "At first, I must admit, I was quite taken in. I thought it was a genuine message. Then the \emdash  er \emdash  person became abusive."
\par "Abusive?"
\par "Most abusive. I was quite alarmed."
\par "Used threatening language, eh?"
\par "Yes. I am not accustomed to being threatened."
\par "What did they threaten you with? Bodily damage?"
\par "Not exactly."
