\par "If you please, madam."
\par "Let me see." She reflected a moment. "I was here. In this house."
\par "Oh!" I saw the inspector's eyes flash. "And your maid \emdash  you have only one maid, I think \emdash  can confirm that statement?"
\par "No, it was Hilda's afternoon out."
\par "I see."
\par "So, unfortunately, you will have to take my word for it," said Mrs. Lestrange pleasantly.
\par "You seriously declare that you were at home all the afternoon?"
\par "You said between six and seven, inspector. I was out for a walk early in the afternoon. I returned some time before five o'clock."
\par "Then if a lady \emdash  Miss Hartnell, for instance \emdash  were to declare that she came here about six o'clock, rang the bell, but could make no one hear and was compelled to go away again \emdash  you'd say she was mistaken, eh?"
\par "Oh! no," Mrs. Lestrange shook her head.
\par "But \emdash "
\par "If your maid is in, she can say not at home. If one is alone and does not happen to want to see callers \emdash  well, the only thing to do is to let them ring."
\par Inspector Slack looked slightly baffled.
\par "Elderly women bore me dreadfully," said Mrs. Lestrange. "And Miss Hartnell is particularly boring. She must have rung at least half a dozen times before she went away."
\par She smiled sweetly at Inspector Slack.
\par The inspector shifted his ground.
\par "Then if any one were to say they'd seen you out and about then \emdash "
\par "Oh! but they didn't, did they?" She was quick to sense his weak point. "No one saw me out, because I was in, you see."
\par "Quite so, madam."
\par The inspector hitched his chair a little nearer.
\par "Now I understand, Mrs. Lestrange, that you paid a visit to Colonel Protheroe at Old Hall the night before his death."
\par Mrs. Lestrange said calmly: "That is so."
\par "Can you indicate to me the nature of that interview?"
\par "It concerned a private matter, inspector."
\par "I'm afraid I must ask you to tell me the nature of that private matter."
\par "I shall not tell you anything of the kind. I will only assure you that nothing which was said at that interview could possibly have any bearing upon the crime."
\par "I don't think you are the best judge of that."
\par "At anyrate, you will have to take my word for it, inspector."
\par "In fact, I have to take your word about everything."
\par "It does seem rather like it," she agreed, still with the same smiling calm.
\par Inspector Slack grew very red.
\par "This is a serious matter, Mrs. Lestrange. I want the truth \emdash " He banged his fist down on a table. "And I mean to get it."
\par Mrs. Lestrange said nothing at all.
\par "Don't you see, madam, that you're putting yourself in a very fishy position?"
\par Still Mrs. Lestrange said nothing.
\par "You'd be required to give evidence at the inquest."
\par "Yes."
\par Just the monosyllable. Unemphatic, uninterested. The inspector altered his tactics.
\par "You were acquainted with Colonel Protheroe?"
\par "Yes, I was acquainted with him."
\par "Well acquainted?"
\par There was a pause before she said:
\par "I had not seen him for several years."
\par "You were acquainted with Mrs. Protheroe?"
\par "No."
\par "You'd excuse me, but it was a very unusual time to make a call."
\par "Not from my point of view."
\par "What do you mean by that?"
\par "I wanted to see Colonel Protheroe alone. I did not want to see Mrs. Protheroe or Miss Protheroe. I considered this the best way of accomplishing my object."
\par "Why didn't you want to see Mrs. or Miss Protheroe?"
\par "That, inspector, is my business."
\par "Then you refuse to say more?"
\par "Absolutely."
\par Inspector Slack rose.
\par "You'll be putting yourself in a nasty position, madam, if you're not careful. All this looks bad \emdash  it looks very bad."
\par She laughed. I could have told Inspector Slack that this was not the kind of woman who is easily frightened.
\par "Well," he said, extricating himself with dignity, "don't say I haven't warned you, that's all. Good\_afternoon, madam, and mind you we're going to get at the truth."
\par He departed. Mrs. Lestrange rose and held out her hand.
\par "I am going to send you away \emdash  yes, it is better so. You see, it is too late for advice now. I have chosen my part."
\par She repeated in a rather forlorn voice:
\par "I have chosen my part."
\par 
