\par }\pard\plain \fi567\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\lang1033\cgrid0 "Very glad to have met you," said Lawrence. "Come to my place."
\par We turned in at the little rustic gate, went up the path, and he drew a key from his pocket and inserted it in the lock.
\par "You keep the door locked now," I observed.
\par "Yes." He laughed rather bitterly. "Case of stable door when the steed is gone, eh? It is rather like that. You know, padre," he held the door open and I passed inside, "there's something about all this business that I don't like. It's too much of 
\emdash  how shall I put it \emdash  an inside job. Someone knew about that pistol of mine. That means that the murderer, whoever he was, must have actually been in this house \emdash  perhaps even had a drink with me."
\par "Not necessarily," I objected. "The whole village of St. Mary Mead probably knows exactly where you keep your toothbrush and what kind of tooth powder you use."
\par "But why should it interest them?"
\par "I don't know," I said, "but it does. If you change your shaving cream it will be a topic of conversation."
\par "They must be very hard up for news."
\par "They are. Nothing exciting ever happens here."
\par "Well, it has now \emdash  with a vengeance."
\par I agreed.
\par "And who tells them all these things anyway? Shaving cream and things like that?"
\par "Probably old Mrs. Archer."
\par "That old crone? She's practically a half\_wit, as far as I can make out."
\par "That's merely the camouflage of the poor," I explai
ned. "They take refuge behind a mask of stupidity. You'll probably find that the old lady has all her wits about her. By the way, she seems very certain now that the pistol was in its proper place midday Thursday. What's made her so positive all of a sudd
en?"
\par "I haven't the least idea."
\par "Do you think she's right?"
\par "There again I haven't the least idea. I don't go round taking an inventory of my possessions every day."
\par I looked round the small living\_room. Every shelf and table was littered with miscellaneous articles. Lawrence lived in the midst of an artistic disarray that would have driven me quite mad.
\par "It's a bit of a job finding things sometimes," he said, observing my glance. "On the other hand, everything is handy \emdash  not tucked away."
\par "Nothing is tucked away, certainly," I agreed. "It might perhaps have been better if the pistol had been."
\par "Do you know I rather expected the coroner to say something of the sort. Coroners are such asses. I expected to be censured or whatever they call it."
\par "By the way," I asked, "was it loaded?"
\par Lawrence shook his head.
\par "I'm not quite so careless as that. It was unloaded, but there was a box of cartridges beside it."
\par "It was apparently loaded in all six chambers and one shot bad been fired."
\par Lawrence nodded.
\par "And whose hand fired it? It's all very well, sir, but unless the real murderer is discovered I shall be suspected of the crime to the day of my death."
\par "Don't say that, my boy."
\par "But I do say it."
\par He became silent, frowning to himself. He roused himself at last and said:
\par "But let me tell you how I got on last night. You know, old Miss Marple knows a thing or two."
\par "She is, I believe, rather unpopular on that account."
\par Lawrence proceeded to recount his story.
\par He had, following Miss Marple's advice, gone up to old Hall. There, with Anne's assistance, he had had an interview with the parlourmaid. Anne had said simply:
\par "Mr. Redding wants to ask you a few questions, Rose."
\par Then she had left the room.
\par Lawrence had felt somewhat nervous. Rose, a pretty girl of twenty\_five, gazed at him with a limpid gaze which he found rather disconcerting.
\par "It's \emdash  it's about Colonel Protheroe's death."
\par "Yes, sir."
\par "I'm very anxious, you see, to get at the truth."
\par "Yes, sir."
\par "I feel that there may be \emdash  that someone might \emdash  that \emdash  that there might be some incident \emdash "
\par At this point Lawrence felt that he was not covering himself with glory, and heartily cursed Miss Marple and her suggestions.
\par "I wondered if you could help me?"
\par "Yes, sir?"
\par Rose's demeanour was still that of the perfect servant, polite, anxious to assist, and completely uninterested.
\par "Dash it all," said Lawrence, "haven't you talked the thing over in the servants' hall?"
\par This method of attack flustered Rose slightly. Her perfect poise was shaken.
\par "In the servants' hall, sir?"
\par "Or the housekeeper's room, or the bootboy's dugout, or wherever you do talk? There must be }{\i\lang1033\cgrid0 some}{\lang1033\cgrid0  place."
\par Rose displayed a very faint disposition to giggle, and Lawrence felt encouraged.
\par "Look here, Rose, you're an awfully nice girl. I'm sure you must understand what I'm feeling like. I don't want to be hanged. I didn't murder your master, but a lot of people think I did. Can't you help me in any way?"
\par I can imagine at this point that Lawrence must have looked extremely appealing. His handsome head thrown back, his Irish blue eyes appealing. Rose softened and capitulated.
\par "Oh! sir, I'm sure \emdash  if any of us could help in any way. None of us think you did it, sir. Indeed we don't."
\par "I know, my dear girl, but that's not going to help me with the police."
\par "The police!" Rose tossed her head. "I can tell you, sir, we don't think much of that inspector. Slack, he calls himself. The police indeed."
\par "All the same, the police are very powerful. Now, Rose, you say you'll do your best to help me. I can't help feeling that there's a lot we haven't got at yet. The lady, for instance, who called to see Colonel Protheroe the night before he died."
\par "Mrs. Lestrange?"
\par "Yes, Mrs. Lestrange. I can't help feeling there's something rather odd about that visit of hers."
\par "Yes, indeed, sir, that's what we all said."
\par "You did?"
\par "Coming the way she did. And asking for the colonel. And of course there's been a lot of talk \emdash  nobody knowing anything about her down here. And Mrs. Simmons, she's the housekeeper, sir, she gave it as her opinion that she 
was a regular bad lot. But after hearing what Gladdie said, well, I didn't know what to think."
\par "What did Gladdie say?"
\par "Oh! nothing, sir. It was just \emdash  we were talking, you know."
\par Lawrence looked at her. He had the feeling of something kept back.
\par "I wonder very much what her interview with Colonel Protheroe was about."
\par "Yes, sir."
\par "I believe you know, Rose?"
\par "Me? Oh I no, sir. Indeed I don't. How could I?"
