\par "Surely not."
\par "Oh! yes, they will. Especially when \emdash " She paused and then said: "When the six months are up \emdash  I am going marry Lawrence." Her eyes met mine. "We're neither of us going to wait any longer."
\par "I supposed," I said, "that that would happen."
\par Suddenly she broke down, burying her head in her hands.
\par "You don't know how grateful I am to you \emdash  you don't know. We'd said good\_bye to each other \emdash  he was going away. I feel \emdash  I feel not so awful about Lucius's death. If we'd been planning to go away together, and he'd died then 
\emdash  it would be so awful now. But you made us both see how wrong it would be. That's why I'm grateful."
\par "I, too, am thankful," I said gravely.
\par "All the same, you know," she sat up. "Unless the real murderer is found they'll always think it was Lawrence \emdash  oh! yes, they will. And especially when he marries me."
\par "My dear, Dr. Haydock's evidence made it perfectly clear \emdash "
\par "What do people care about evidence? They don't even know about it. And medical evidence never means anything to outsiders anyway. That's another reason why I'm staying on here. Mr. Clement, }{\i\lang1033\cgrid0 I'm going to find out the truth}{
\lang1033\cgrid0 ."
\par Her eyes flashed as she spoke. She added:
\par "That's why I asked that girl here."
\par "Miss Cram?"
\par "Yes."
\par "You did ask her, then. I mean, it was your idea?"
\par "Entirely. Oh! as a matter of fact, she whined a bit. At the inquest \emdash  she was there when I arrived. No, I asked her here deliberately."
\par "But surely," I cried, "you don't think that that silly young woman could have anything to do with the crime?"
\par "It's awfully easy to appear silly, Mr. Clement. It's one of the easiest things in the world."
\par "Then you really think?"
\par "No, I don't. Honestly, I don't. What I do think is that that girl knows something \emdash  or might know something. I wanted to study her at close quarters."
\par "And the very night she arrives, that picture is slashed," I said thoughtfully.
\par "You think she did it? But why? It seems so utterly absurd and impossible."
\par "It seems to me utterly impossible and absurd that your husband should have been murdered in my study," I said bitterly. "But he was."
\par "I know." She laid her hand on my arm. "It's dreadful for you. I do realise that, though I haven't said very much about it."
\par I took the blue lapis lazuli ear\_ring from my pocket and held it out to her.
\par "This is yours, I think?"
\par "Oh! yes." She held out her hand for it with a pleased smile. "Where did you find it?"
\par But I did not put the jewel into her outstretched hand.
\par "Would you mind," I said, "if I kept it a little longer?"
\par "Why, certainly." She looked puzzled and a little inquiring. I did not satisfy her curiosity.
