\par "It is an impertinent question," I said, "but I really do not mean it as such."
\par "I don't think it's impertinent at all. You and Griselda are the best friends I have here. And I like that funny old Miss Marple. Lucius was very well off, you know. He left things pretty equally divided betw
een me and Lettice. Old Hall goes to me, but Lettice is to be allowed to choose enough furniture to furnish a small house, and she is left a separate sum for the purpose of buying one, so as to even things up."
\par "What are her plans, do you know?"
\par Anne made a comical grimace.
\par "She doesn't tell them to me. I imagine she will leave here as soon as possible. She doesn't like me \emdash  she never has. I dare say it's my fault, though I've really always tried to be decent. But I suppose any girl resents a young stepmother."
\par "Are you fond of her?" I asked bluntly.
\par She did not reply at once, which convinced me that Anne Protheroe is a very honest woman.
\par "I was at first," she said. "She was such a pretty little girl. I don't think I am now. I don't know why. Perhaps it's because she doesn't like me. I like being liked, you know."
\par "We all do," I said, and Anne Protheroe smiled.
\par I had one more task to perform. That was to get a word alone with Lettice Protheroe. I managed that easily enough, catching sight of her in the deserted drawing\_room. Griselda and Gladys Cram were out in the garden.
\par I went in and shut the door.
\par "Lettice," I said, "I want to speak to you about something."
\par She looked up indifferently.
\par "Yes?"
