\par "Then it looks, doesn't it," said Lettice coolly, "as though she hadn't spoken the truth?"
\par "You mean that she came right in and stood by the desk?"
\par "Well, it looks like it, doesn't it?"
\par Her eyes met mine serenely.
\par "If you want to know," she said calmly, "I never have thought she was speaking the truth."
\par "And I }{\i\lang1033\cgrid0 know you}{\lang1033\cgrid0  are not, Lettice."
\par "What do you mean?"
\par She was startled.
\par "I mean," I said, "that the last time I saw this ear\_ring was on Friday morning when I came up here with Colonel Melchett. It was lying with its fellow on your stepmother's dressing\_table. I actually handled them both."
\par "Oh \emdash  !" She wavered, then suddenly flung herself sideways over the arm of her chair and burst into tears. Her short fair hair hung down almost touching the floor. It was a strange attitude \emdash  beautiful and unrestrained.
\par I let her sob for some moments in silence and then I said very gently:
\par "Lettice, why did you do it?"
\par "What?"
\par She sprang up, flinging her hair wildly back. She looked wild \emdash  almost terrified.
\par "What do you mean?"
\par "What made you do it? Was it jealousy? Dislike of Anne?"
\par "Oh! \emdash  oh! yes." She pushed the hair back from her face and seemed suddenly to regain complete self\_possession. "Yes, you can call it jealousy. I've always disliked Anne \emdash 
