\par As I rose to my feet I noticed a small brownish crystal lying on the ground. Almost automatically, I picked it up and slipped it into my pocket.
\par Then grasping my find by the handle, I retraced my steps to the path.
\par As I climbed over the stile into the lane, an agitated voice near at hand called out:
\par "Oh! Mr. Clement. You've found it! How clever of you!"
\par Mentally registering the fact that in the art of seeing without being seen, Miss Marple had no rival, I balanced my find on the palings between us.
\par "That's the one," said Miss Marple. "I'd know it anywhere."
\par This, I thought, was a slight exaggeration. There are thousands of cheap shiny suit\_cases all exactly alike. No one could recognise one particular one seen from such a distance away by moonlight, but I realised that the whole business of the suit\_
case was Miss Marple's particular triumph and, as such, she was entitled to a little pardonable exaggeration.
\par "It's locked, I suppose, Mr. Clement?"
\par "Yes. I'm just going to take it down to the police station."
\par "You don't think it would be better to telephone?"
\par Of course unquestionably it would be better to telephone. To stride through the village, suit\_case in hand, would be to court a probably undesirable publicity.
\par So I unlatched Miss Marple's garden gate and entered the house by the French window, and from the sanctity of the drawing\_room with the door shut, I telephoned my news.
\par The result was that Inspector Slack announced he would be up himself in a couple of jiffies.
\par When he arrived it was in his most cantankerous mood.
\par "So we've got it, have we?" he said. "You know, sir, you shouldn't keep things to yourself. If you've any reason to believe you know where the article in question was hidden, you ought to have reported it to the proper authorities."
